The Schnitzel House is an icon of Bay Ridge earned through hard work, delicious food and unbelievable service. They hand cook everything at the time of order so don't expect fast food, but you can count on great food. The owners, Fred and Amber treat everyone like family, welcoming every guest with a smile. They make rounds to each table to ensure each guest has a positive dining experience.   Our waiter, Dean provided exemplary table service from start to finish. This was our first time eating here, and we are not familiar with German fare. He took the time to explain the dishes we were interested in, and also recommended some favorites from the menu. For the appetizers we chose the fried camembert (which came with fried parsley and jam) and the mushroom truffle pierogies. Both were outstanding. Our main course was the Wurst sampler, which we shared. Each wurst was unique and delicious, the sides/mustards complimented every bite perfectly. Gracious hosts, delicious food and good conversation. Thanks for a delightful evening, we will definitely be back!

My friend and I were very disappointed with our dinner when we dined there 2 weeks ago. I had been there before so this seemed to be an anomaly.  We both ordered the prime ribs ...and I ordered mine medium rare. When the waiter arrived with our dinner, in my opinion, that was NOT prime ribs. Even with the steak knife, it was horribly tough...and it was well done. I hesitated to tell the waiter but I did. Not even an apology and off he went.  I'm not one to leave food on my plate....but the "prime ribs"...which, imo, was a skirt or a flank steak, was horrible....the vegetables were barely cooked (what is this? A Chinese restaurant???) and the mashed potatoes were questionable. If you looked at my plate, it looked as if I had a few bites. My friend was in agreement with me about her dinner as well.  Now onto our appetizers....my friend ordered shrimp cocktail. The shrimp were not cold as shrimp in a shrimp cocktail should be & her cocktail sauce was warm. My appetizer was mussels. Most were very small and dry and the broth lay at the bottom of the dish in less than an inch.  The waiter passed out table many times, glanced at our almost full plates & never said a word. We're pretty sure he knew exactly we weren't pleased with our dinner but never asked if "anything is wrong" or "Can I get you dessert" or "do you want anything else". Nothing. We left him a $2.00 tip.  Never again.  PS....the saving grace were the rolls. Warm & tasty...not the best.  Oh...and the butter was delicious!! Those were the butter pats served in little packages.  We'll never return !!!!

My family and I have came into the location under the initial impression that credit cards were accepted, however the person at the front had let us know that it is a cash only place. With that minor set back, my family and I proceeded to go to an atm, gather money and head back to restaurant, since, we were all excited to try this place because of all the ratings. Yes, the very center may have been medium well, but the rest wasn’t close to medium rare at all. I really don’t like to argue at restaurants, so I paid the bill, walked away and don’t plan to come back. I believe that they could have done a better customer service, but they chose not to. So, if you like a good prime rib, you may play your luck, but don’t expect much.

Where to begin with this place? So many things were just awful. Let's start with the food had a bowl of spicy goulash the beef in it was tough and just plain bad for a stew it should really soften that meat up but nope you'd be surprised, I ate about 5% of it. The saurbraten was inedible meat was horrible dry   flavorless despite the sweet and sour sauce with seemed watered down. I politely expressed to the server that I don"t really like my dish and, would really like to send it back perhaps order something else in its place.   from what I assume she  goes to ask a "manager" . After a very akward silence and some choice whispering coming from the bar she returns and tells me nope there is nothing she can do. she says to my surprise "I can't take it back I can't reserve it" After a very troubling thought that they would evan try to reserve it. I look around and realize Evan if they did try to reserve it there would be no one to reserve it to. it was empty on a Saturday night with good reason. "Manager" "owner" made no effort to inquire about why I did not like the dish instead forced it on to the check with no alternative or accommodation, just a like it or not don't care. Gave two stars because I did have a wurst sampler as well and it was actually edible, and the beer selection was varied. I have been a culinary professional for nearly twenty years, and would like to offer a word of advice to this business, customers keep your doors open, unsatisfied ones keep them closed. please remind management and kitchen staff to have integrity in what they serve. I will not be returning to the haus and will detour all my friends and family alike.  as a sidenote it's 2016 accepting credit cards wouldn't be a bad thing either  of course it's your choice. Back to the food for dessert I had the German chocolate cake. In my best words it tasted like when you leave something way to long in the fridge and it takes the taste of the refrigerator, that about sums up the flavor on this one old and dried out. I really wanted to like this place  but they failed on so many levels, I have dedicated a tremendous amount of time and passion to the service industry and culinary arts that it's sad and disappointing when a restaurant puts shame to a country's food by serving sub par dishes with no willingness to try to resolve or engage its guests. Ohhhh I almost forgot bread was for sure old it was rubbery and stale  a warm up would of truly helped it out so much. In no way does this reflect our servers performance  she does what she  is told by management  and preforms her job to the best of her ability to which I thank her for

I said this is not the point, maybe I do not have $180.00 in cash? He got really nasty and brought me to the front door to point out the sign that no one paid attention to; stated we do not accept credit cards on Sunday’s and Wednesday’s Their was another family there that also wanted to pay by credit card and did not understand this concept either. I personally think that those are their busiest days and are avoiding paying taxes on how much money they really make on those days (My Assumption). Therefore I will never step foot in there on a Sunday or Wednesday. I want to see how they will pay your vendor’s if no one steps foot in tht place again on those days. You need to change this crazy rule. Who in this day, in this economy has $150.00 or more in their pockets for lunch?
